Yukos to invest four bln dlrs in foreign projects 
Russian oil giant Yukos plans to invest four billion dollars in foreign
projects by 2005, company chairman Mikhail Khodorkovsky said Wednesday.
Yukos, the country's second largest producer, intends to spend two
billion dollars of its own funds and raise another two billion dollars
from foreign investors for a number of oil refining projects in the
West, the Interfax news agency reported.
Another possible Yukos project is a major chain of petrol stations in
Germany.
The largest company on the Moscow stock exchange, Yukos estimates
output in 2002 at between 68 and 70 billion tonnes of crude, compared
with 58.07 million tonnes in 2001.
